#### P1035 summation of series

> **DESCRIPTION**
> Known: Sn= 1+1/2+1/3+…+1/n. 
> It’s obvious that for any integer k when integer n is big enough, Sn>k.
> Now give an integer k. Please find the smallest n which makes Sn>k.
> **INPUT FORMAT**
> A positive integer k.
> **OUTPUT FORMAT**
> A positive integer n.
> **SAMPLE**
> Input		Output
> 1				2
> 
> 
> **TIPS**
> For 100% data, 1<=k<=15

It should be noted that: integer data cannot appear in floating-point operations, otherwise it becomes an integer operation.

```c++
#include<iostream>
using namespace std;


int main()
{
	int n=0;
	int k=0;
	double sn=0.0000;//Pay attention to data accuracy
	double temp=0.0000;//Pay attention to data accuracy 

	cin>>k;
	while(sn<=k)
	{
		n++;
		temp=1.0000/n;//do not use int data 
		sn=sn+temp;
	}

	cout<<n;

	return 0;

}
```

